So, in the time I've been here, it's been my understanding that there was a gentlemen's agreement of sorts that likes go to comments which "add to the discussion", even if the specific point of view is something the liker disagrees with. Here's the thing though: we shouldn't need to like in order to determine what adds to the discussion. Certainly some fairly straightforward heuristics like Flesch-Kincaid (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flesch%E2%80%93Kincaid_readability_test) Grade Level times number of replies (possibly adding in a factor for the F-K Grade Level of the replies to weed out long chains of drivel) should be relatively good at picking the best posts.
I'm not saying that liking should be eliminated entirely, but maybe it becomes just part of the heuristic. Imagine something like BCS standings, but for comments. Even like tallies could become smarter, with likes from "trusted" users counting more heavily than those from "noobs" or well known rabble-rousers.

Finally, I think it would be really neat (assuming you like my proposal of a combined heuristic in place of liking) if the algorithm was open source. Take the Google view of "if you don't like the results, don't special case the outcomes, improve the algorithm!" This would have the added benefit of giving the world a first-class comment value sorting algorithm vetted by some of the top talent in the world, and dog-food-ed on a site where they care deeply about the quality of the discussion.

while i personally dont find this image that funny, i understand what could make it funny, 
for an obvious breakdown of the joke; it is a perversion of the ideals set forth by MLK Jr. here, proposing that the type of equality he campaigned for was one of grisly retribution. to think that a man of peace and wisdom would look down from the heavens and smile at the idea of slavery and inequality still existing but with the roles merely reversed is crazy and false, and it is this play of expectations and boundary pushing that makes some people find it funny. the boundary pushing is what makes it especially funny to some, because the taboo is less expected and the less expected has a greater potential for humor. it is also what makes it more uncomfortable to some. i think that this group exists (at least defined by the content submitted until now) in some ways as peoples safe-place to submit unsafe content. unsafe insofar as that the content does not concern itself with making people comfortable but only with its own absurdness.
Ah shit - hold on, deleting my original response Matt. Was on mobile and it was posted before I had a chance to comb it over.

its true, all of the things that make me slightly uncomfortable about this image relate to its ambiguous origins and not the actual content, oddly enough. something about the low quality of the image, the compression, the black border, make me group it with other images involving race that come from a potentially hateful place, images from a slightly different internet, when content was different possibly because the means of distribution were different, while this image's content seems too unorganized/absurd to be directed towards hate. i suppose it is undeniable that the medium is the message, at least in regards to how we choose to perceive things.

Indeed! There is little I can disagree with here, insofar as explaining the joke goes, but I think there is a certain context missing - who created it, what consciously or subconsciously motivated them to do so, etc. An interesting issue I find is a lot of posts here are divorced of their original source. Lacking that information, I assume the worst of jokes being made involving race because I find the idea of being "colorblind" counterproductive and often insensitive. Pushing boundaries and searching for absurdity are fine - that's why I'm here. I never take the position that a certain class of joke should be forbidden from being told, but at the very least I find this photo kind of crass and stupid.
the low hanging fruit gets eaten

Couldn't tell you anything additional about the source other then that it was sent to me by my 14 year old sister. And as a new member I can't comment on any problematic racial aspects to the group or its intended purpose. I'm black and find the image hilarious, politically incorrect, and absurd. Moralizing something as right or wrong is tiresome to me as I believe both art and morality are entirely subjective constructs. Phrasing an issue as a questions strikes me as lazy and/or timid, since it puts the ownness of addressing your own concern on someone else.

 Calling something crass or stupid isn't an argument, its a subjective opinion. That type of vague opinion is both boring and difficult to respond to. The large amount of likes on the photo demonstrates a segment of the group that finds the image in some way entertaining. On the converse, some many find it crass and stupid. In my mind that doesn't matter at all. WHY or WHAT about the image made you feel uncomfortable? That's what I'm curious to know. Appreciate your contributions to the conversation all the same.

Calling the photo crass and stupid wasn't the end all be all of my argument, it was more just an added thought. I could have left it out I suppose. As to phrasing issues as questions - would you prefer people not try at all? Like, Jesus man, not everyone is comfortable just putting themselves out on the Internet. Some people are timid, some people are lazy, whatever. Sometimes you just want to ask the question to put it out there, see if people are willing to respond at all. Put yourself in their shoes, assume good faith.

You declaration of art and morality as subjective seems more like an attempt to build an unfalsifiable position - which is fine, I suppose, as long as you don't want your position on the photo confronted.

What makes me uncomfortable about the photo is, essentially, that as a joke on race it's not really nuanced and I can't be sure if people are laughing at it for the wrong reasons. Seeing reverse-slavery as a one-shot joke and MLK as essentially a reverse-racism Obi-Wan cheapens what might have been decent satire.

I mean, I'm getting mixed signals here - on the one hand you imply my contributions are timid, lazy, and boring on the span of a few sentences, but you value them anyway?

I get that discussions like these are frustrating - a lot of times I also prefer not getting into one. And at every post I question how much I'm going to get out of what I'm putting in. But if this group is about some higher purpose than just posting ridiculous stuff, I haven't seen it demonstrated much. So I decided to go for it.

What position? That art / morality is subjective and the viewer is free to interpret the image posted however they choose? I'd love for you to confront that position. The phrasing of objections as questions by anyone strikes me as some form of timidity / sloth, yes, and yes, I do find attempts to reduce intellectual discourse to vauge 101 adjectives like crass and stupid boring.

 In taking my descriptors as personally aimed at your character you make a logical assumption / misstep, taking things personally when you shouldn't.  I definitely value your willingness to put yourself out there as a white male regarding the infinitely testy subject of race.  I'm simply trying to gauge why or what actually makes you feel that way? In my mind that's the only part of the argument I'm interested in. Whether an individual finds it stupid and crass or intellectually lofty and subtle or whatever amalgamation of adjectives  means nothing to me because it says nothing to me. Apologies if that seems harsh.

I don't really care whether my whiteness comes into play here, don't worry about it. I earnestly didn't mean to imply that I was brave for starting this - I guess I just wanted to ensure people wouldn't quit after being frustrated. But it's you and I only at this point. :)

Your position being that the image you posted is not possibly problematic (unless I have misinterpreted you), and that even if it is, holding it to be problematic is entirely subjective. If something being problematic cannot be judged as right or wrong, what reason is there to address whatever makes it problematic? How can we be motivated to correct any injustice at all (not to be too broad). Perhaps that clarifies what I mean?

I may have taken your words personally - I admit my error there. However, calling a method of starting discourse lazy and timid also seems irrelevant to the present discourse as it stands. I guess in the future I'll try to be more assertive, if it's any comfort.
